SLAPNAP Report: VRC01

SLAPNAP Team

27 May, 2020

1 Executive summary

The broadly neutralizing antibody (bnAb) studied in this analysis is VRC01. The analysis considered 2 measures of neutralization sensitivity: IC-50 and sensitivity. Sensitivity is defined by the binary indicator that IC-50 < 1. Based on this specification of bnAb and outcomes:

  • 828 sequences were extracted from the CATNAP database (Yoon et al. 2015);

  • 825 sequences had complete geographic and genetic sequence information;

  • 828 of these sequences had measured IC\(_{50}\). ;

  • out of the sequences with complete data, 115 were estimated to be resistant to the antibody, while 713 were estimated to be sensitive.

Prediction of each outcome was performed using random forest (Breiman 2001) with tuning parameters set to their ‘default’ values.

The specific algorithm used in the learning process is described in Table 1.1.

Table 1.1: Algorithms used in the analysis
Label Description
SL.ranger.reg random forest with mtry equal to square root of number of predictors

The predictive ability of the learner was assessed using cross-validation. The estimated cross-validated \(R^2\) of the super learner for predicting IC-50 is shown in Table 1.2. The estimated cross-validated area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC) of the super learner for predicting sensitivity is shown in Table 1.3.

Table 1.2: Estimates of 2-fold cross-validated \(R^2\) for super learner predictions of IC-50 (n = 825 observations with complete sequence data).
CV - R^2 Lower 95% CI Upper 95% CI
IC-50 0.339 0.29 0.384
Table 1.3: Estimates of 2-fold cross-validated AUC for super learner predictions of sensitivity (n = 825 observations with complete sequence data).
CVAUC Lower 95% CI Upper 95% CI
Sensitivity 0.79 0.743 0.83
